title: Investigation about a statement equivalent to Riemann Hypothesis (RH)

sections.text:
## ABSTRACT

We try to approach a known equivalence to RH involving relative maxima and minima of $\xi(s)$ on critical line by a representation of the derivative of the phase of $\xi(s)$ with respect to imaginary coordinate that involves directly Euler product. In this attempt it is found an object conjectured to be, almost everywhere, the converging "spectrum" of prime numbers. Reasons and consequences of the conjecture are highlighted.

MSC-Class : 11M06, 11M99
Keywords: Riemann hypothesis, Riemann spectrum of primes, Prime numbers, Riemann zeta function, Euler product

## CONTENTS

1. Introduction 1
2. Analytic phase variation of $\xi(s)$ along $t$ 2
2.1. Angular Momentum of the $\xi$ function, and his $\epsilon$ variation 4
2.2. LEMMA 1 4
3. Phase variation of $\xi(s)$ function using the Euler product 5
3.1. Conjecture on extended convergence of (3.21) and (3.22) 9
4. Consequences of conjecture of subsection 3.1 10
4.1. LEMMA 2: $\frac{\partial \angle[\xi(t, \epsilon)]}{\partial t}$ and Euler product 10
4.2. LEMMA 3: estimate of sign of $\frac{\partial^{2} \Im[\ln (\zeta(s)(s-1))]}{\partial s \partial t}$ 11
4.3. THEOREM 1 : variation of $\{\mathcal{L}[\xi(s)]\}_{\epsilon \approx 0}$ with $\epsilon$ 14
5. Conclusions 15

References 15
Appendix A. Numerical comparisons between $\frac{\partial \angle[\xi(t, \epsilon)]}{\partial t}$ and (3.21) 16

## 1. InTRODUCTION

This paper is linked to a previous one [12] on Dirichlet functions. We use the following known relations: Riemann $\zeta(s)$ function, (see also [2], [4], [5, p. 229]), is defined as the analytic continuation of the function:

$$
\zeta(s)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^{s}}=\prod_{\forall p} \frac{1}{1-\frac{1}{p^{s}}} \quad(p \text { prime }) \quad \Re(s)>1
$$

The strip $0<\Re(s)<1$ is called critical strip, the line $\Re(s)=1 / 2$ is the critical line, and, the infinite product is called Euler Product. The complex

[^0]
[^0]:    ${ }^{1}$ giolodone3@gmail.com

argument $s$ is expressed throughout as:

$$
s=\frac{1}{2}+\epsilon+i t
$$

so that $\epsilon$ is the distance from critical line ,and, $t$ is the imaginary coordinate. A key function is $\xi(s)[5$, p. 16], that is real on the critical line and has the same zeros of $\zeta(s)$ in the critical strip:

$$
\xi(s)=\Gamma\left(\frac{s}{2}+1\right)(s-1) \pi^{-s / 2} \zeta(s)=\left[\frac{\Gamma\left(\frac{s}{2}+1\right)}{\pi^{s / 2}}\right] \times[\zeta(s)(s-1)]
$$

RH statement is:
" the analytic continuation of $\zeta(s)$ has all non trivial zeros, $s_{0}$, on $\Re[s]=$ $1 / 2$ ( i.e. on critical-line) ".
The equivalence stated in $[3$, p. 6] is reported here for easy reading:
"The Riemann hypothesis is equivalent to the statement that all local maxima of $\xi(t)=\xi\left(\frac{1}{2}+i t\right)$ are positive and all local minima are negative, . . ." .
This article is structured as follows:

- In section 2 is shown that the above equivalence is linked to $\frac{\partial \epsilon^{\prime} \xi(s)}{\partial t}$, and,a numerical example is given.
- In section 3 a similar expression, $\frac{\partial \Im\{\ln [\zeta(s)(s-1)]\}}{\partial t}$, is computed using Euler product. It is proved that this representation is valid at least for $\epsilon>1 / 2$. Besides reasons are listed to conjecture a more wide area of validity.
- In section 4, by application of above conjecture, it is proved, with similar arguments in [12, p. 11], that

$$
\forall t \text { with } \xi(t) \neq 0 \text { we have }\left(\frac{d \xi(t)}{d t}\right)^{2}-\xi(t) \times \frac{d^{2} \xi(t)}{d t^{2}}>0
$$

. Where $\xi(t)=\xi(1 / 2+i t)$.

- In section 5 results are summarized and concluding remarks are given.
- In appendix some numerical example are given.

# 2. ANALYTIC PHASE VARIATION OF $\xi(s)$ ALONG T 

The phase of $\xi(s)$ function can be computed using Wolfram Mathematica by RiemannSiegelZ function, or, the result is the same ( see [11]), by [10]. Through a positive scale factor $F(t)=(\pi / 2)^{0.25} t^{\frac{7}{4}} e^{-\frac{\pi}{4} t}$ and hyperbolic functions plus other terms here omitted. The expression is:
$\frac{-\xi(t, \epsilon)}{F(t) e^{i \epsilon^{\frac{5}{4}}}} \approx Z(t, \epsilon)=2 \sum_{n=1}^{N} \frac{\cosh \left[\epsilon \ln \left(\sqrt{\frac{t}{2 \pi n^{2}}}\right)\right]}{\sqrt{n}} \cos \left(t \ln \left(\sqrt{\frac{t}{2 e \pi n^{2}}}\right)-\frac{\pi}{8}\right)$

where $N=\left\lfloor\sqrt{\frac{t}{2 \pi}}\right\rfloor$ and:

$$
R_{0}(t, \epsilon)=(-1)^{N-1}\left(\frac{2 \pi}{t}\right)^{1 / 4}\left[C_{0}(p)\right]
$$

with $p=\sqrt{\frac{t}{2 \pi}}-N$. In (2.2), the dependence from $\epsilon$ has been neglected ([10, p. 1]). Besides ([10, p. 16]):
(2.3) $C_{0}(0.5) \leq C_{0}(p)=\frac{\left(\cos \left(2 \pi\left(p^{2}-p-\frac{1}{16}\right)\right)\right.}{\cos (2 \pi p)} \leq \cos \left(\frac{\pi}{8}\right)=C_{0}(0)=C_{0}(1)$
![img-0.jpeg](img-0.jpeg)

Figure 1: Phase of $Z(t, \epsilon)=\angle[\xi(t, \epsilon)]$ (2.1), in the interval $-\pi . .+\pi$ , versus $t$, with $\epsilon$ as parameter. Zeros are at $t^{*} \approx 1645.5737, t^{*} \approx$ $1646.624, t^{*} \approx 1648.270, t^{*} \approx 1649.118$.

We can compute $\frac{\partial \angle[\xi(s)]}{\partial t}$ for $\epsilon \neq \epsilon_{k}^{*}$, where $\xi\left(1 / 2+\epsilon_{k}^{*}+i t_{k}^{*}\right)=0 \forall k$. Of course for $\epsilon<\epsilon^{*}$ the peaks of fig 2 computed with $Z(t, \epsilon)$ are negative. We know that at least for the first $10^{13}$ zeros $\epsilon^{*}=0,[6]$. While the phase variation of factor $\left[\frac{\Gamma\left(\frac{s}{2}+1\right)}{\pi^{s / 2}}\right]$ in (1.3) is from [12, p. 18-20]:
(2.4)
$\frac{\partial \angle\left[\Gamma\left(\frac{s}{2}+1\right) \pi^{-s / 2}\right]}{\partial t}=\left[\frac{\partial\left[\Im_{1}+\Im_{2}+\Im_{3}\right]}{\partial t}\right]=\frac{1}{2} \ln \left(\frac{t}{2 \pi}\right)+O\left(t^{-2}\right) ;$ for $\epsilon \rightarrow 0$ then $O\left(t^{-2}\right) \rightarrow \frac{3 \epsilon}{4 t^{2}}$
For $\epsilon \rightarrow 0, O\left(t^{-2}\right) \rightarrow \frac{3 \epsilon}{4 t^{2}}$ because with a few more additional developments $\left(\left[\frac{\partial^{2} \Im_{1}}{\partial \epsilon \partial t}\right]_{\epsilon=0}=0\right.$, and, neglecting $\left[\frac{\partial^{2} \Im_{2}}{\partial \epsilon \partial t}\right]_{\epsilon=0}$ ), we have:

![img-1.jpeg](img-1.jpeg)

Figure 2: Derivative of $\angle[\xi(t, \epsilon)]$ with respect to $t$ by phase of $Z(t, \epsilon)$ ( 2.1 ), with $\epsilon$ as parameter.
$\left\{\frac{\partial^{2} \angle\left[\left(\frac{\pi}{9}\right)^{-\frac{s}{2}} \Gamma\left(\frac{s+2}{2}\right)\right]}{\partial \epsilon \partial t}\right\}_{\epsilon=0}=\left[\frac{\partial^{2}\left[\Im_{1}+\Im_{2}+\Im_{3}\right]}{\partial \epsilon \partial t}\right]_{\epsilon=0} \approx\left[\frac{\partial^{2} \Im_{2}}{\partial \epsilon \partial t}\right]_{\epsilon=0}=\frac{3}{4 t^{2}}$
The part of (1.3) connected with peaks in fig. 2 at $t^{*}=\Im\left[\rho^{*}\right]$ is:

$$
[\zeta(s)(s-1)], \text { i.e. } \frac{\partial \angle[\zeta(s)(s-1)]}{\partial t}
$$

2.1. Angular Momentum of the $\xi$ function, and his $\epsilon$ variation.

As in $[12$, p. 3$]$ we define angular momentum $\mathcal{L}[\xi(s)]$ :
(2.5)
$\operatorname{DEFINITION} 1 \quad \mathcal{L}[\xi(s)]:=\operatorname{det}\left(\begin{array}{cc}\Re \xi(s) & \Im \xi(s) \\ \frac{\partial}{\partial t} \Re \xi(s) & \frac{\partial}{\partial t} \Im \xi(s)\end{array}\right)=|\xi(s)|^{2} \frac{\partial \angle[\xi(s)]}{\partial t}$
Since $\Im \xi=0$ for $\epsilon=0$, we have $\mathcal{L}[\xi(s)]=0$ on the critical line. From Lemma 1 in $[12$, p. 3$]$ we have: $\mathcal{L}[C \times \xi(s)]=|C|^{2} \mathcal{L}[\xi(s)]$, where $C \in$ Complex field. So $\operatorname{Sign}[\mathcal{L}[\xi(s)]]=\operatorname{Sign}[\mathcal{L}[Z(t, \epsilon)]$.

# 2.2. LEMMA 1. 

As in $[12$, p. 4$]$ we have:
(2.6)

$$
\left[\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}[\xi(t, \epsilon)])}{\partial \epsilon}\right]_{\epsilon=0}=\operatorname{det}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\xi(t) & -\xi^{\prime}(t) \\
\xi^{\prime}(t) & -\xi^{\prime \prime}(t)
\end{array}\right)=\left[\xi^{\prime}(t)\right]^{2}-\xi(t) \xi^{\prime \prime}(t), \text { where }, \xi(t))=\xi(1 / 2+i t)
$$

PROOF: see $[12$, p. 4]
It is apparent that equivalence [3, p. 6], reported here p. 2, can be expressed with

$$
\left[\xi^{\prime}(1 / 2+i t)\right]^{2}-\xi(1 / 2+i t) \xi^{\prime \prime}(1 / 2+i t)>0 \quad \forall t
$$

# 3. Phase variation of $\xi(s)$ function using the Euler product 

Following $[5$, p. 25])) we have:
$\ln (\zeta(s))=\ln (\xi(0))+\sum_{\rho} \ln \left(1-\frac{s}{\rho}\right)-\ln \left(\Gamma\left(\frac{s}{2}+1\right)\right)+\frac{s}{2} \ln (\pi)-\ln (s-1) ;\{\Re(s)>1\}$
But notice that $\left\{\Re(s)>0, \forall t \neq t_{k}^{*}\right\}$ at least :
$\ln (\zeta(s)(s-1))=\ln (\xi(0))+\sum_{\rho} \ln \left(1-\frac{s}{\rho}\right)-\ln \left(\Gamma\left(\frac{s}{2}+1\right)\right)+\frac{s}{2} \ln (\pi) ;\left\{\Re(s)>0, \forall t \neq t_{k}^{*}\right\}$ at least
By (3.1) Riemann found the distribution of $J(x)$,

$$
J(x)=\frac{1}{2}\left[\sum_{p^{n}<x} \frac{1}{n}+\sum_{p^{n} \leq x} \frac{1}{n}\right]
$$

, i.e. the "number of prime powers till $x$ ", from (3.1) for $x>1$ ( $[5$, p. 34]) :
(3.4)
$J(x)=L i(x)-\sum_{\rho} L i\left(x^{\rho}\right)-\ln (2)+\int_{x}^{\infty} \frac{d y}{y\left(y^{2}-1\right) \ln (y)}=L i(x)-\sum_{\rho} L i\left(x^{\rho}\right)-\ln (2)$
Or ( $[5$, p. 36]):
(3.5)
$d J(x)=\left[\frac{1}{\ln (x)}-2 \sum_{\Im \rho>0} \frac{x^{\Re \rho-1}}{\ln (x)} \cos [\Im \rho \ln (x)]-\frac{1}{x\left(x^{2}-1\right) \ln (x)}\right] d x \quad ; \quad x>1$
The term $\int_{x}^{\infty} \frac{d y}{y\left(y^{2}-1\right) \ln (y)}$, wich stems from trivial zero, is a term that can be neglected, and $\frac{1}{\ln (x)}$ is the density of the local mean value of prime powers .
So :
(3.6)
$J(x)-L i(x)=-\sum_{\rho} L i\left(x^{\rho}\right)-\ln (2) \quad \rightarrow \quad d[J(x)-L i(x)]=-2 \sum_{\rho} \frac{d x}{} \frac{x^{\Re \rho-1}}{\ln (x)} \cos [\Im \rho \ln (x)] ; \quad \rho=\Re \rho \pm i \Im \rho$
$J(x)$ is related to $\pi(x)$, the number of prime first powers till $x$, by [5, p. 33]):
(3.7)

$$
J(x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\left\lfloor\frac{\ln (x)}{\ln (2)}\right\rfloor} \frac{\pi\left(x^{1 / n}\right)}{n} \quad, \text { and the inverse, } \quad \pi(x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\left\lfloor\frac{\ln (x)}{\ln (2)}\right\rfloor} \frac{\mu(n)}{n} J\left(x^{1 / n}\right)
$$

where $\mu(n)$ is Moebious function [2].
Riemann used a transform relation between $J(x)$ and $\zeta(s)$ [5, p. 22]) ( integral is in Stieltjes sense [1] ) giving ([5, p. 22])):

$$
\ln (\zeta(s))=\sum_{p} \sum_{n} \frac{1}{n p^{n s}}=\int_{0}^{\infty} x^{-s} d[J(x)] ; \Re[s]>1
$$

Whose inverse trasform, applied to all pieces of (3.1), (see tab. 1) can be written as ( $[5$, p. 25])) :

$$
J(x)=-\frac{1}{\ln (x) 2 \pi i} \int_{a-i \infty}^{a+i \infty} \frac{d}{d s}\left[\frac{\ln (\zeta(s)}{s}\right] x^{s} d s \quad ; \quad a>1
$$

We are interested in $\angle[\zeta(s)(s-1)]=\Im[\ln (\zeta(s)(s-1)]$ of (3.2), and, in using Euler Product at $\Re(s)<1$.
Notice that condition $R e[s]>1$ in (3.8) is due to left term: $\ln (\zeta(s))$, and to the purpose of using trasforms (see tab. 1 ).
Notice also that $\angle[z]=\Im[\ln (z)]$, but caution is needed if $z$ is real negative, where $\arctan (\Im[z], \Re[[z])$ is defined, and, can be continuous, while complex logarithm experiences a $2 \pi$ phase discontinuity, so makes sense that $\frac{\partial \Im[\ln (\zeta(s)(s-1)]}{\partial t}$ diverges to $+\infty$ across $t=t^{*}, \epsilon \leq \epsilon^{*}$, with $\zeta\left(1 / 2+\epsilon^{*}+i t^{*}\right)=$ 0 .
Let us focus on left part of (3.2). It converges for $\{\Re(s)>0\} \backslash$ \{Singular p.\}.
For $R e(s)>0$ singular points are: the $\zeta(s)$ non trivial zeros, $s=\rho_{k}^{*}=$ $\frac{1}{2}+\epsilon_{k}^{*}+i t_{k}^{*}$, and the segments from them normal to axis $\operatorname{Re}(s)=0$ where there is a discontinuity, along $t$, i.e. a $2 \pi$ step, of $\angle[\zeta(s)(s-1)]$ computed as $\Im[\ln (\zeta(s)(s-1))]$.
Because the two factors of (1.3), are defined $\forall s$, while trasforms only for $\Re(s)>1$, we can write, using 3rd row of tab. 1 , at least :

$$
\ln [\zeta(s)(s-1)]=\int_{0}^{\infty} x^{-s} d[J(x)-L i(x)] ; \quad
$$

Left term of (3.10) is defined surely for $\{\Re(s)>0\} \backslash\{$ Singular $p$.$\}$, right term, let us say, for $\{\Re(s)>\alpha\}$, where $\alpha$ is discussed below.
We want to extract phase variation of $\zeta(s)(s-1)$ along $t$ from (3.10).
In order to trade resolution along $t$ with computational burden it is convenient to address to mean phase variation in an interval $\left(t_{1}, t_{2}\right)$.
We consider $t$ increment in order to compute incremental ratio with respect to $t$, and, define the value $p^{*}$ so that:

$$
t_{2}=t+\frac{\pi}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)} \quad ; \quad t_{1}=t-\frac{\pi}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)} ; \quad \Delta t=\frac{2 \pi}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}
$$

The phase of $\zeta(s)$, through Euler product, is given by:

$$
\angle\left[\zeta_{E P}(s)\right]=\Im[\ln \left(\zeta_{E P}(s)\right)]=-\sum_{p} \angle\left[1-\frac{1}{p^{s}}\right]=\sum_{p} \arctan \left(\frac{-\sin (\ln (p) t)}{p^{1 / 2+\epsilon}-\cos (\ln (p) t)}\right) \quad \epsilon>1 / 2
$$

![table_0](table_0)

Table 1: Trasform pairs used by Riemann to find (3.4).
and, using an ad hoc notation, mean phase variation through Euler Product :
(3.13)

$$
\left\{\frac{\Delta \angle\left[\zeta_{E P}(s)\right]}{\Delta t}\right\}_{p^{*}, p_{\max }}=-\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{2 \pi} \sum_{p \rightarrow p_{\max }} \arctan \left(\frac{\sin (\ln (p) t)}{p^{1 / 2+\epsilon}-\cos (\ln (p) t)}\right)\left.\right|_{t_{1}} ^{t_{2}} \epsilon>1 / 2
$$

The Imaginary part of $-\int_{0}^{\infty} x^{-s} d[L i(x)]$, is :

$$
\Im\left[-\int_{0}^{\infty} x^{-s} d[L i(x)]\right]=\int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{\sin (\ln (x) t)}{x^{1 / 2+\epsilon}} d[L i(x)] \quad, \epsilon>1 / 2
$$

We want to find the mean value of phase variation in interval $\left(t_{1}, t_{2}\right)$, like in (3.11), as above, so, we set $\Delta t=t_{2}-t_{1}$ and define accordingly the value $p^{*}$. As $\sin \left(\ln (p) t_{2}\right)-\sin \left(\ln (p) t_{1}\right)=2 \cos (\ln (p) t) \sin \left(\frac{\pi \ln (p)}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}\right)$, using above ad hoc notation, the mean phase variation in $t_{1}, t_{2}$ is:

$$
\left\{\frac{\Delta\left\{\Im\left[-\int_{p=2}^{p=p_{\max }} x^{-s} d[L i(x)]\right\}\right.}{\Delta t}\right\}_{p^{*}, p_{\max }}=\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{\pi} \int_{p=2}^{p=p_{\max }} \frac{\cos (\ln (x) t)}{x^{1 / 2+\epsilon}} \sin \left(\frac{\pi \ln (x)}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}\right) d[L i(x)], \epsilon>1 / 2
$$

Using incremental ratio for (3.6) with (3.11) as above, we have:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left\{\frac{\Delta\left\{\Im\left[\int_{p=2}^{p=p_{\max }} x^{-s} d[J(x)-L i(x)]\right]\right\}}{\Delta t}\right\}_{p^{*}, p_{\max }}=\left\{\frac{\Delta\left\{\Im\left[-\int_{p=2}^{p=p_{\max }} x^{-s} d\left[\sum_{\rho} L i\left(x^{\rho}\right)\right]\right\}}{\Delta t}\right\}_{p^{*}, p_{\max }}= \\
\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{\pi} \int_{2}^{p_{\max }} \frac{\cos (\ln (x) t)}{x^{1 / 2+\epsilon}} \sin \left(\frac{\pi \ln (x)}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}\right) d\left[\sum_{\rho_{k}} L i\left(x^{\rho_{k}}\right)\right]= \\
\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{\pi} \int_{2}^{p_{\max }} \frac{\cos (\ln (x) t)}{x^{1 / 2+\epsilon}} \sin \left(\frac{\pi \ln (x)}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}\right)\left[2 \sum_{\rho_{k}} \frac{d x}{} \frac{x^{3 l} \rho_{k}-1}{\ln (x)} \cos \left[\Im \rho_{k} \ln (x)\right]\right]=
\end{gathered}
$$

$$
\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{\pi} \int_{2}^{p_{\max }} \sum_{p^{*}} \frac{d x}{x} \frac{x^{e^{*}-\epsilon}}{x \ln (x)} \cos [\Im \rho \ln (x)] \cos [t \ln (x)] \sin \left(\frac{\pi \ln (x)}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}\right)
$$

Where : $\quad \rho_{k}^{*}=\Re \rho_{k}^{*} \pm i \Im \rho_{k}^{*}$ are the non trivial zeros. If $\epsilon_{M A X}^{*}=M a x\left[\epsilon_{k}^{*}\right], \forall k$, then for $\epsilon>\epsilon_{M A X}^{*}$, (3.16) converges absolutely $\forall p_{\max } \geq p^{*} \rightarrow \infty$.
This is apparent posing $e^{y}=x$, so for (3.16) :

$$
\left\{\frac{\Delta\left\{\Im\left[\int_{p=2}^{p=p_{\max }} x^{-s} d[J(x)-L i(x)]\right]\right\}}{\Delta t}\right\}_{p^{*}, p_{\max }}=\left\{\frac{\Delta\left\{\Im\left[-\int_{p=2}^{p=p_{\max }} x^{-s} d\left[\sum_{\rho} L i\left(x^{\rho}\right)\right]\right\}}{\Delta t}\right\}_{p^{*}, p_{\max }}=
$$

$$
\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{\pi} \int_{\ln (2)}^{\ln (p_{\max })} \frac{\cos (y t)}{e^{(1 / 2+\epsilon) y}} \sin \left(\frac{\pi y}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}\right)\left[2 \sum_{\rho_{k}} \frac{d y}{\rho_{k}} \frac{e^{\left(\epsilon_{k}^{*}+1 / 2\right) y}}{y} \cos \left[\Im \rho_{k} y\right]\right]=
$$

The square bracket in intermediate lines of (3.16) and (3.19 is $d(J(x)-$ $L i(x))$. The factor $e^{\left(\epsilon_{k}^{*}-\epsilon\right) y}$ in (3.19 forces the integrals to converge for $\epsilon>\epsilon_{k}^{*}$. So $\alpha$ of definition halfplane for (3.10) right term is at least

$$
0.5+\epsilon_{M A X}^{*}=\Re(s)=\alpha<1
$$

because no roots $\rho^{*}$ on $\Re(s)=1$ are possible. See [5, p. 69]).
From previous Lemmas, and considering third row of tab. 1 , we can write right part of (3.10), at least for $\Re(s)>1$, as:

$$
\left\{\frac{\Delta \Im[\ln \{\zeta(s)(s-1)\}]}{\Delta t}\right\}_{p^{*}, p_{\max }}=\left\{\frac{\Delta \angle\left[\zeta_{E P}(s)\right]}{\Delta t}\right\}_{p^{*}, p_{\max }}-\left\{\frac{\Delta\left\{\Im\left[\int_{p=2}^{p=p_{\max }} x^{-s} d[L i(x)]\right\}\right.}{\Delta t}\right\}_{p^{*}, p_{\max }}=
$$

$$
\left.-\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{2 \pi}\left\{\left[\sum_{p=2}^{p_{\max }} \arctan \left(\frac{\sin (\ln (p) t)}{p^{1 / 2+\epsilon}-\cos (\ln (p) t)}\right)\right]_{t-\frac{\pi}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}}^{t+\frac{\pi}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}}-\int_{2}^{p_{\max }} \frac{2 \cos (\ln (x) t)}{x^{1 / 2+\epsilon}} \sin \left(\frac{\pi \ln (x)}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}\right) d[L i(x)]\right\}=
$$

Below we speculate that right part of (3.10), i.e. like (3.22) or (3.21), have actually converging features well beyond $\Re[s]>1$.

sections.text:
# 3.1. Conjecture on extended convergence of (3.21) and (3.22). 

Expressions (3.21), and (3.22) are conjectured to converge to same number (i.e. $\frac{\partial \Im[\ln (\zeta(s)(s-1))]}{\partial t}$ ) not only $\forall \epsilon>1 / 2$, irrespective of zeros placement, but, also for $t \neq t_{k}^{*}, \forall \epsilon>-|\delta|$ where $0<|\delta|<0.5$. And also for $t=t_{k}^{*}$, and $\epsilon>\epsilon_{k}^{*}$, with $\zeta\left(1 / 2+\epsilon_{k}^{*}+i t_{k}^{*}\right)=0$.
Using an approximation like (3.4) in [12, p. 6], neglectinging a finite error difference, we could write an expression whose difference from (3.21) is finite:
$-\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{\pi} \int_{p=2}^{p=p_{\max }} \frac{\cos (\ln (x) t)}{x^{1 / 2+\epsilon}} \sin \left(\frac{\pi \ln (x)}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}\right) d[\pi(x)-L i(x)]<+\infty ; \epsilon \geq 0 ; t \neq t_{k}^{*}$
So also (3.23), would converge like (3.22), at least, $\forall \epsilon \geq 0$, irrespective of zeros place.
This conjecture does not exclude singular points of $\frac{\partial \Im[\ln (\zeta(s)(s-1))]}{\partial t}$.
Perhaps, no one of the reasons in the list below is a proof. But, if they are taken all together, they give some merit (numerical, intuitive, heuristic, aesthetic . . .) in order to take into consideration this conjecture.

- Right and left term of (3.2) converge, excluding singular points, at least for $\epsilon>-1 / 2$. Expression (3.2) comes from right term of (3.1) upon subtracting $\ln \left(\frac{1}{(s-1)}\right)$. Following tab. 1 (third row) it produces an $L i(x)$ term that becomes (3.15) after incremental ratio (3.11) processing. Instead $\ln (\zeta(s))$, after same elaboration, becomes (3.13). Both are diverging for $\epsilon<1 / 2$ if taken alone. But taken together?. For (3.2) their algebric sum seems to tend to $\frac{\partial \Im[\ln (\zeta(s)(s-1))]}{\partial t}$, as if computed from (3.2) at least for $\epsilon>-|\delta|>-1 / 2$. Otherwise we would reach conflicting results only following different paths of permissible calculations, i.e derivative along $t$ of phase of (3.2), and, (3.21). This could be perhaps a proof, but, is better to be cautious.
- From (3.15 ) and, (3.16) it is apparent that right part of (3.10) have peaks at $t=\Im\left[\rho_{k}^{*}\right], \epsilon \leq \epsilon_{k}^{*}$ where $\xi\left(\rho_{k}^{*}=1 / 2+\epsilon_{k}^{*}+i t_{k}^{*}\right)=0$. Lemma 3 PROOF.
Let us take a close view at $\cos (\ln (p) t)$ oscillations in (3.22). The expression is:
$\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{\pi} \int_{2}^{p_{\max }} \frac{\cos (\ln (x) t)}{x^{1 / 2+\epsilon}} \sin \left(\frac{\pi \ln (x)}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}\right) d[J(x)-L i(x)] \quad$, with $\ln \left(p^{*}\right)$ big

- Zero transition at increasing $\cos [\ln (x) t]$ :

$$
x_{0 t}(k)=e^{(2 \pi k-\pi / 2) / t} \quad \text { increasing } \quad \text { cosine }
$$

- Zero transition at decreasing $\cos [\ln (x) t]$ :

$$
x_{0 t}^{\prime}(k)=e^{(2 \pi k+\pi / 2) / t} \quad \text { decreasing } \quad \text { cosine }
$$

Positive contribution for (4.2) integrand, is given by prime powers inside the exponentially growing (with $k$ ) interval $\Delta x_{k}$ (subscript $0 t$ means 'zero transition'):
(4.5) $x_{0 t}^{\prime}(k)-x_{0 t}(k)=x_{0 t}(k)\left[e^{(\pi / t)}-1\right] \approx \frac{\pi}{t} e^{(2 \pi k-\pi / 2) / t}=\frac{\pi}{t} x_{\text {mean }}=\Delta x_{k}$

while, negative contribution is given by prime powers inside the exponentially growing (with $k$ ) interval $\Delta x_{k}^{\prime}$ :

$$
x_{0 t}(k+1)-x_{0 t}^{\prime}(k)=x_{0 t}^{\prime}(k)\left[e^{(\pi / t)}-1\right] \approx \frac{\pi}{t} e^{(2 \pi k+\pi / 2) / t}=\frac{\pi}{t} x_{\text {mean }}^{\prime}=\Delta x_{k}^{\prime}
$$

So each $t$ choice partitions prime powers in two sets. The positive, and, the negative contributors to (4.2).

Looking at (4.2) we can split the integral in subintervals: .. $\Delta x_{k-1}, \Delta x_{k-1}^{\prime}, \Delta x_{k}, \Delta x_{k}^{\prime}, \Delta x_{k+1}, \Delta x_{k+1}^{\prime}, \ldots$. See (4.6), and (4.5).
In $\Delta x_{k}$ intervals $((4.5)) J(x)$ gives a positive contribution:

$$
O_{J}^{+}(\epsilon)_{k}=\left|\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{\pi} \int_{p>x_{0 t}(k)}^{p<x_{0 t}^{\prime}(k)} \frac{\cos [\ln (p) t] \sin \left[\pi \ln (p) / \ln \left(p^{*}\right)\right]}{\sqrt{p} p^{\epsilon}} d J(p)\right|
$$

while $L i(x)$ a negative one:

$$
O_{L i}^{-}(\epsilon)_{k}=\left|\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{\pi} \int_{p>x_{0 t}(k)}^{p<x_{0 t}^{\prime}(k)} \frac{\cos [\ln (p) t] \sin \left[\pi \ln (p) / \ln \left(p^{*}\right)\right]}{\sqrt{p} p^{\epsilon}} d[L i(p)]\right|
$$

In $\Delta x_{k}^{\prime}$ intervals $J(x)$ gives a negative contribution:

$$
O_{J}^{-}(\epsilon)_{k}=\left|\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{\pi} \int_{p>x_{0 t}^{\prime}(k)}^{p<x_{0 t}(k+1)} \frac{\cos [\ln (p) t] \sin \left[\pi \ln (p) / \ln \left(p^{*}\right)\right]}{\sqrt{p} p^{\epsilon}} d J(p)\right|
$$

while $L i(x)$ a postive contribution:

$$
O_{L i}^{+}(\epsilon)_{k}=\left|\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{\pi} \int_{p>x_{0 t}^{\prime}(k)}^{p<x_{0 t}(k+1)} \frac{\cos [\ln (p) t] \sin \left[\pi \ln (p) / \ln \left(p^{*}\right)\right]}{\sqrt{p} p^{\epsilon}} d[L i(p)]\right|
$$

The four above are positive definite quantities. Signs are made explicit when they are assembled together. Then (4.2), using (4.7), (4.8 ), (4.9 ), (4.10), can be written also as :

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}{\pi} \int_{2}^{p_{\max }=x_{k_{\max }+1}} \frac{\cos (\ln (x) t)}{x^{1 / 2+\epsilon}} \sin \left(\frac{\pi \ln (x)}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}\right) d[J(x)-L i(x)]= \\
\sum_{k}^{k_{\max }}\left\{O_{J}^{+}(\epsilon)_{k}-O_{L i}^{-}(\epsilon)_{k}-O_{J}^{-}(\epsilon)_{k}+O_{L i}^{+}(\epsilon)_{k}\right\}

Grouping must not alter the order of the sum because there is not absolute convergence. For our choices, in the $k$-th oscillation, in the space of primes, $O_{J}^{+}(\epsilon)_{k}$ comes before $O_{J}^{-}(\epsilon)_{k}$, and, $O_{L i}^{-}(\epsilon)_{k}$ comes before $O_{L i}^{+}(\epsilon)_{k}$.

Of course it goes to 1 because the difference between numerator and denominator is of lower order with respect to them. This is true in a continuous way also considering fractions of oscillations. Apart the absolute value of cosine shape, the common factor $\left|\frac{\sin \left(\pi \ln (p) / \ln \left(p^{*}\right)\right)}{p^{1 / 2+\epsilon}}\right|$ and the alternating choice between $J(x)$ and $L i(x)$. The same cosine shape $\left|\cos (\ln (p) t) \frac{\sin \left(\pi \ln (p) / \ln \left(p^{*}\right)\right)}{p^{1 / 2+\epsilon}}\right|$ at numerator or denominator, or, ending with a fractional interval does not change the limit. # 5. Conclusions 

We found an expression (3.22) that is a correlation between: (1) difference of prime powers distribution, $J(x)$, from the mean $L i(x)$, and, (2) a weighted $\cos (\ln (x) t)$. It can be interpreted as the "spectrum of primes". In (3.22) formulation, the zeros of $\zeta(s)$ are the $t$-abscissa of correlation peaks of $d[J(x)-L i(x)]$, with the weighted $\cos (\ln (x) t)$, along $x$.
We are free to choose resolution (changing $\epsilon$ and $p^{*}$ ) at will, and maximum number of primes involved $\left(p_{M A X}\right)$. With $\epsilon-\epsilon_{k}^{*} \leq 0$ (see (4.1 ) ) we have that the peak at $\epsilon=\epsilon_{k}^{*}, t=t_{k}^{*}$ becomes a ridge in the $\left|t-t_{k}^{*}\right|<\frac{2 \pi}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}$ region, like in $\frac{\partial \Im[\ln (\zeta(s)(s-1))]}{\partial t}$. This ridge shrinks, along $t$, as $p^{*} \rightarrow \infty$ even if it is prohibitive from a computational point of view. See fig. 3, and, fig 6. If conjecture, whose rationale is explained in subsection 3.1, is true, then this "spectrum of primes" converges, at least, for $p_{\max } \geq p^{*} \rightarrow \infty$, at least in $0 \leq \epsilon \leq 1 / 2, \forall t \neq t_{k}^{*}$.
Besides we have conditional Theorem 1 in section (4.3) that says us that where $\xi(t) \neq 0$, and, $\xi^{\prime}(t)=0$, then $\xi(t) \times \xi^{\prime \prime}(t)<0$. So this result addresses directly the equivalence stated in [3, p. 6]. See page 2 here. Statement (4.3) does not exclude double zeros on critical line, as it would be if we could erase $\xi(t) \neq 0$ condition in (4.3).
The similarity with theorem in [12, p. 11] about Dirichlet odd primitive characters is obvious.
The proof of (4.3 shows also that if an off-critical line zero exists at $t_{\text {off }}^{*}$, in an open interval of $t_{\text {off }}^{*}$ then $\left[\xi^{\prime}(t)\right]^{2}-\xi(t) \xi^{\prime \prime}(t)>0$, as in each single zero with $\epsilon^{*}=0$, and, wherever $t \neq t_{k}^{*}$, i.e. (4.3 is a weak version of (2.7). Then, the existence of even one off-critical line zero would contradict the above equivalence. Conditional Theorem 1 here leaves only the possibility of single zeros or, if any, double zeros, but on critical line. Exactly like the unconditional theorem in [12, p. 11] about Dirichlet primitive characters

When $\epsilon$ is greater than zero like in this case, $\epsilon=+0.1$, we need comparatively less primes, with respect to $\epsilon=0$, to attain the shape of $\frac{\partial \angle[\xi(s)]}{\partial t}$ computed by (2.1). It is like a filtering of high frequency, $\frac{\ln (p)}{2 \pi}$, i.e. high $p$ contributions.

Figure 5: Plotted with (3.21) at fixed $T$, and, with $p_{\max }$ from 2 till $3 \times 10^{6}$. We can see the stabilization trend at increasing primes at different $\epsilon$ values. Stabilization is reached at greater primes with lower algebraic $\epsilon$. Notice $\epsilon$ values from -0.1 to 0.1

Figure 6: Computation of (3.21) with $p_{\max }=60 \times 10^{6}$ and $p^{*}=$ $6 \times 10^{6}$ with a sliding window of length $W=\frac{2 \pi}{\ln \left(p_{\max }\right)}=\frac{2 \pi}{\ln \left(6 \times 10^{6}\right)}$ to counteract Gibbs Phenomenon. The shift on $t$ axis is not compensated. Notice that, for $\left|t-t_{k}^{*}\right|>\frac{2 \pi}{\ln \left(p^{*}\right)}$, curves with lower $\epsilon$ are below curve with higher $\epsilon$ as predicted by Lemma 3. If we put $p_{\max }=p^{*}=6 \times 10^{6}$ we get a plot similar to this one, if then we do smoothing with $W=$ $\frac{2 \pi}{\ln \left(p_{\max }\right)}=\frac{2 \pi}{\ln \left(6 \times 10^{6}\right)}$ we get, practically, this same figure. Notice the greater positive peak for negative $\epsilon$. It is due to the discontinuity of $\Im[\ln (\zeta(s)(s-1))]$ along $t=t_{k}^{*}, \epsilon \leq \epsilon_{k}^{*}$, here $=0$.

abstract:
We try to approach a known equivalence to RH involving relative maxima and
minima of Xi(t) on critical line by a representation of the derivative of the
phase of Xi(s) with respect to imaginary coordinate that involves directly
Euler product. In this attempt it is found an object conjectured to be the ,
almost everywhere, converging "spectrum" of prime numbers . Reasons and
consequences of the conjecture are highlighted.
